      "message": "Patch Set 3: Verified+1\n\nTests uploaded by Onyx Autotest from onyx-32vm1 for review-dne-part-3 received by maloo, run on CentOS Linux 7/x86_64: (https://testing.hpdd.intel.com/test_sessions/e450b2a2-6433-47fb-9019-96ec899b3763). Ran 3 tests. No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "3dece7fe9c454180cc04438e55a6ebaae452cef9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-05-06 15:56:46.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "62318b4142261c8cd2d3374c7587873229f11274",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-05-06 15:57:43.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nNote that when the other patch lands, only this patch will need to be debased to resolve the conflicts. The later patches in the series do not need to be rebased if they do not have conflicts.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "847a25bac940598b938bb6e63e136569852fa1c6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2018-05-06 17:12:11.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n> Note that when the other patch lands, only this patch will need to\n > be debased to resolve the conflicts. The later patches in the\n > series do not need to be rebased if they do not have conflicts.\n\nNot quite, I suspect.\n\nThis patch shows as dependent on change 30792 for whatever reason. So what really needs to happen is this patch to be based on the tip of master.\n\nBecause of this dependency hpdd checkpatch does not show up with the -1 \"no longer applies\" warning.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "6092825795f43a54c78a70c51c987fd880f97888",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 443,
        "name": "Andrew Perepechko",
        "email": "andrew.perepechko@hpe.com",
        "username": "panda"
      },
      "date": "2018-05-08 04:40:27.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nAFAIR, one of the reasons the initial T10 patch was abandoned was the requirement from Intel to update the design and network protocols so that different checksumming models can be used, not just T10, but also Merkle tree based, and not use separate connection flags for each checksumming type. However, this patch sticks to a single protocol and single connection flag. Has anything changed since then? Wouldn't it be easier just to rework the original patch than duplicating that work ? I cannot remember any terrible defects in it that require rewriting everything from scratch. Lustre itself does not benefit from splitting a single feature into phases either - it just makes coding easier.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "c257d8ac7f2c7f1d539eb08f0ee336837b9be18f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-05-08 05:00:33.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n> AFAIR, one of the reasons the initial T10 patch was abandoned was\n > the requirement from Intel to update the design and network\n > protocols so that different checksumming models can be used, not\n > just T10, but also Merkle tree based, and not use separate\n > connection flags for each checksumming type. However, this patch\n > sticks to a single protocol and single connection flag. Has\n > anything changed since then? Wouldn't it be easier just to rework\n > the original patch than duplicating that work ? I cannot remember\n > any terrible defects in it that require rewriting everything from\n > scratch. Lustre itself does not benefit from splitting a single\n > feature into phases either - it just makes coding easier.\n\nAndrew, the other reason the previous T10-PI patch was unpleasant was that it sent all of the T10-PI GRD tags over the network (it might have also sent the APP and REF tags, I don't recall).  Even with only the GRD tags, it would be 2 bytes/sector, or 4KB of extra data for a 1MB RPC.  For a 16MB RPC it would be 64KB of extra data, which would be very inefficient.\n\nOne benefit of the new patch is the checksum-of-checksums approach, which reduces the 4KB (or 64KB) to a 32-bit checksum that can easily fit into the existing Lustre RPC checksum field.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "75b488ab08a74750d834c034a735b720d6ee818a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 443,
        "name": "Andrew Perepechko",
        "email": "andrew.perepechko@hpe.com",
        "username": "panda"
      },
      "date": "2018-05-08 05:27:43.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nAndreas, thank you for the clarification. It looks like the design is hidden in discussion and not easy to follow. However, if we just send a different kind of single checksum, is the new connection flag really needed? OSC checksums already support different algorithms.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "7d603db4c94b7eb312b04cbc70d70c99311d90c3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 337,
        "name": "Li Xi",
        "email": "lixi@ddn.com",
        "username": "LiX"
      },
      "date": "2018-05-08 14:12:47.000000000",
      "message": "Abandoned\n\nT10PI doesn't need extra connect flag now. It uses checksum types.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    }
  ],
